entry.title: SQL: Ensure CorruptSizeInHeader is using exclusive mode
entry.content:
The corruptSizeInHeader function is used in unittests to

corrupt the database on disk.



If the database is opened in WAL, it requires a checkpoint to

ensures the data is moved from the journal to the actual database

(a.k.a sqlite3_wal_checkpoint_v2(...)).



This CL is ensuring the database is opened in exclusive mode;

which means there is no other opened instance of that database.

If there was instances, CorruptSizeInHeader(...) will fail and

return false. The corresponding unittests will fail and should be

fixed.



Bug: 1120969

entry.title: camera: Fix race conditions in CameraHalDelegate's deconstruction
entry.content:
Since LocalCameraClientObservers are removed after

ResetMojoInterfaceOnIpcThread is called, SetCameraModule may be

scheduled after ResetMojoInterfaceOnIpcThread. In this case,

camera_module_ will not be reset on ipc_thread_.

This CL

1. removes observers first then resets the mojo connection to ensure

thread safety.

entry.title: Don't include disabled types in the supported types
entry.content:
FormGroup::GetSupportedTypes() return a ServerFieldTypeSet indicating

for which ServerFieldTypes the group can store values. This is used

to determine for which types the FormGroup should vote.



When new types are introduced behind a feature flag, they are generally

only exposed through GetSupportedTypes() when that feature flag is

enabled (example [1]).

For new types added as part of the i18n efforts, this is not the case.

This could potentially be a problem during voting, if a user is enrolled

in an experiment, stores data for such a type and then unenrolls from

the experiment, e.g. by restarting the browser. In this case, that

client would continue sending votes.



This CL fixes this problem by overriding AddressComponent::GetTypes()

in FeatureGuardedAddressComponent, similar to the logic that prevents

storing data in the address component when the feature flag is disabled.

entry.title: Move from third_party.toml to cargo-centered approach for 3p rust
entry.content:
The //third_party/rust/chromium_crates_io dir now acts like a cargo

project that provides a crates.io mirror of the crates we use in the

Chromium project.



We generate GN files out of the chromium_crates_io dir into the same

places under //third_party/rust.



This moves to using mostly the same codepaths in gnrt for 3p rust

crates as for stdlib.

- third_party.toml has moved to chromium_crates_io/Cargo.toml

- Cargo.lock has moved to chromium_crates_io/

- `gnrt gen` now builds from chromium_crates_io/Cargo.toml but writes

the BUILD.gn files to the same place.

- `gnrt download` will now do the wrong thing and needs to be removed

or replaced by `cargo vendor` or something else like it.

- Added gnrt_config.toml for 3p crates along with a few flags specific

to 3p crates: allow_first_party_usage, build_script_outputs, group.

- Added remove_build_rs config to avoid having to patch out the

build.rs file in cxx.

- Patches are all moved to //third_party/rust/chromium_crates_io/patches

- Crates only for test are now marked `testonly` in GN, instead of

only applying that to the `test_support` group alias.



The old 3p code paths for generating GN rules in gnrt are left

behind, and are now unused. They will be deleted in a follow up

CL.



The gen.rs function for generated stdlib was forked for generating

3p, but all other functions are shared. More code could be merged

in future CLs.



Next steps:

- Move the GN files from //third_party/rust/X to

//third_party/rust/{safe,sandbox,test}/X (and move the

README.chromium files over)

- Throw errors if a safe crate depends on a sandbox crate.

- Run `cargo vendor` and update crates as a result (we're behind in

ways Cargo does not like at the moment, even with fixed versions

specified). Add `.cargo/config` to point cargo at the `vendor/`

directory for crates. Remove all the crates-io patches in

`Cargo.toml`.

- A script to re-apply all the patches in `patches/` to `vendor/`.

entry.title: [Android][SA] Allow ChromeImageViewPreference to reset its button
entry.content:
This CL allows ChromeImageViewPreference to reset its button on the RHS

when the image resource ID is 0. This is especially useful for recycled

views as so to not inherit wrong recycled buttons.



The current application of this behaviour is for the Storage Access site

settings page. The site settings pages has preferences with both a button

or nothing at all. Without this change, the button was showing up in

preferences that it shouldn't after the page is refreshed because

the buttons were being recycled by preferences that have no image set.

failures when the incorrect overload is selected.



This CL ensures a clearer separation between the move- and copy- use

cases by means of splitting the API into two different functions.

entry.title: Improve A11y Announcement of Content Settings.
entry.content:
Currently, on the category settings pages, each toggle has a title (e.g.

Location) and a subtitle (e.g. Ask before allowing sites to know your

location), with the subtitle changing when the toggle is switched (e.g. to Blocked).



This is not great for accessibility. This CL changes leaves the visible UI unchanged, but changes screen reader announcements such that we announce both states of this toggle at once as two full sentences. entry.title: [//gpu] Move GMB ownership from SIIProxy to ClientSII
entry.content:
This CL moves ownership of the GpuMemoryBuffers associated with

MappableSharedImages out of SharedImageInterfaceProxy and into

ClientSharedImage itself. This will facilitate a followup change that

moves GMB ownership into ClientSharedImage.



Note that there is one behavorial change of interest here:

- Currently, the GMB lives in SharedImageInfo, which is destroyed only

when DestroySharedImage() is called on the *last* reference to the

Mailbox.

- In this change, the GMB is destroyed at the end of

ClientSharedImageInterface::DestroySharedImage(), regardless of

whether this DestroySharedImage() call was on the last reference to

the Mailbox or not.



This behavioral change would break the following theoretical case:

- A MappableSI is created on one SII

- A second SII (backed by the same SIIProxy) adds that Mailbox via

AddReferenceToSharedImage()

- We call MapSharedImage() on that Mailbox on the second SII



However, we currently never create a ClientSI from a Mailbox that was

added via AddReferenceToSharedImage(), so we can never call

MapSharedImage(ClientSI) on such a Mailbox (currently all creation

sites of ClientSharedImage() are within the various

SII::CreateSharedImage() implementations).



If/when we get to the point of needing to support this flow I figure

that at that point we would be passing in a ClientSI to

AddReferenceToSharedImage() and that ClientSI would have obtained the

GMBHandle from the external ClientSI (either via std::move or via

cloning the handle as makes sense given whatever the use case and

performance need is).

entry.title: Save current wallpaper search background to history
entry.content:
A history of 6 wallpaper search themes are saved to history so that a

user can choose it again. This history is kept track of via a list of

token strings saved in prefs.

side panel is closed. This is done by saving to history in the

handler's deconstructor.

added, everything after 6 will not be included in the pref update

and their corresponding file will be deleted.

* If the new entry is already in history, put the new entry at the

front of the history list and keep everything else in relatively the

same order. Example:

original history: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6

new entry: 4

new history: 4, 1, 2, 3, 5, 6

entry.title: Fix resource request related UMA
entry.content:
The following UMAs were introduced by https://crrev.com/c/3613548:

Blink.Loading.CodeCacheArrivalAtRenderer

Blink.Loading.CachedResponseArrivalAtRenderer

But they are not recorded after https://crrev.com/c/4910676 which

removed the logic of setting `code_cache_arrival_time_`.

We are not monitoring them anymore so this CL removes them.



This CL also changes following UMAs more precisely record the IPC delay

by ignoring frozen requests and by recording the time when the

renderer receives the IPC in MojoURLLoaderClient, and adds "2" suffix.

Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay -> StartDelay2

Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay -> ResponseDelay2

Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay -> RedirectDelay

Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay -> CompletionDelay2



Also this CL changes ResourceRequestSender to use the time when the

renderer receives the IPC in MojoURLLoaderClient instead of the time

recorded in ResourceRequestSender for converting the renderer side

timing information from the network service side timing information.

(Technically this can change Resource Timing information. But this

happens only when the page was frozen on pre-Vista Windows.)



OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.Loading.CodeCacheArrivalAtRenderer]=No used.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.Loading.CachedResponseArrivalAtRenderer]=Not used.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.StartDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.ResponseDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.RedirectDelay2.

OBSOLETE_HISTOGRAM[Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay]=Replaced by Blink.ResourceRequest.CompletionDelay2.
